│ The user wants me to fix a miscompilation in LLVM's `instcombine` pass related to the `llvm.copysign` intrinsic. The issue is an incorrect optimization where `copysign(x, y)` is        │
│ transformed into `fneg(fabs(x))` based on a `nofpclass` attribute that indicates the result is never positive. This transformation is invalid when the first operand, `x`, is a NaN.     │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The required fix is to add a check to ensure that the first operand is not a NaN before this optimization is applied. The function `isKnownNeverNaN()` can be used for this purpose. The │
│ relevant code is located in `llvm/lib/Analysis/ValueTracking.cpp`, within the `SimplifyIntrinsic` function, specifically in the `case` for `Intrinsic::copysign`.                        │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ My previous attempts have failed due to two main reasons:                                                                                                                                │
│ 1.  Inability to reliably locate the code to be patched. The environment's search tools (`grep`) are unreliable, and manual browsing is difficult.                                       │
│ 2.  Inability to make file modifications that are detected by the `submit-patch` command. This is likely because each command runs in a new subshell, and my modifications were not      │
│ persisting.                                                                                                                                                                              │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ I have also struggled with creating a correct `diff` patch file because I couldn't get the correct source context. The `patch` command consistently failed with "Hunk #1 FAILED".        │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ I need a new strategy that is robust against these environmental challenges.                                                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ Here's the plan:                                                                                                                                                                         │
│ 1.  I will stop trying to create a `diff` file. The context is too hard to get right.                                                                                                    │
│ 2.  I will go back to modifying the file directly. The key is to do the modification and the submission in the *same* command, chained with `&&`.                                        │
│ 3.  Instead of `sed -i` or `awk`, which have proven unreliable, I will use a simple `sed` command with redirection to a temporary file, and then `mv` to replace the original. This is a │
│ very standard and robust way to edit a file in a script.                                                                                                                                 │
│ 4.  The most critical part is locating the code to modify. I will stop guessing line numbers. I will use a pattern that is very likely to be unique to the target location. The faulty   │
│ optimization is guarded by `if (FC.isKnownNeverPos()) {`. This seems like a good anchor.                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The code to insert is:                                                                                                                                                                   │
│ ```c++                                                                                                                                                                                   │
│       // This transform is not safe for NaNs. The sign of a NaN result from                                                                                                              │
│       // copysign depends on the sign of the second operand. The nofpclass                                                                                                               │
│       // attribute does not restrict the sign of a NaN.                                                                                                                                  │
│       if (!isKnownNeverNaN(Op0))                                                                                                                                                         │
│         return nullptr;                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                      │
│ Note: The original reproducer shows the optimization returning a `Value*`. In `SimplifyIntrinsic`, returning `nullptr` (or `None` in newer LLVM) indicates that the simplification did   │
│ not occur. So `return nullptr;` is the correct action.                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ So, the `sed` command will look for the line `if (FC.isKnownNeverPos()) {` and append my code block after it.                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The full command will be:                                                                                                                                                                │
│ `sed '/if (FC.isKnownNeverPos()) {/a \                                                                                                                                                   │
│       \/* This transform is not safe for NaNs. The sign of a NaN result from*\/ \                                                                                                        │
│       \/* copysign depends on the sign of the second operand. The nofpclass*\/ \                                                                                                         │
│       \/* attribute does not restrict the sign of a NaN. *\/ \                                                                                                                           │
│       if (!isKnownNeverNaN(Op0)) \                                                                                                                                                       │
│         return nullptr;' llvm/lib/Analysis/ValueTracking.cpp > /tmp/vt.cpp && mv /tmp/vt.cpp llvm/lib/Analysis/ValueTracking.cpp && submit-patch`                                        │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ I will use C-style comments `/* ... */` to avoid issues with `sed` and newlines. I will also return `nullptr` as that's the correct way to signal "no simplification" in this context.   │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ sed '/if (FC.isKnownNeverPos()) {/a \                                                                                                                                                    │
│       /* This transform is not safe for NaNs. The sign of a NaN result from\                                                                                                             │
│        * copysign depends on the sign of the second operand. The nofpclass\                                                                                                              │
│        * attribute does not restrict the sign of a NaN. */\                                                                                                                              │
│       if (!isKnownNeverNaN(Op0))\                                                                                                                                                        │
│         return nullptr;' llvm/lib/Analysis/ValueTracking.cpp > /tmp/vt.cpp && mv /tmp/vt.cpp llvm/lib/Analysis/ValueTracking.cpp && submit-patch                                         │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                      │
